<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>
Native American Legends: Evaki (Ewaki)
</H1>





<font size=4>
<b>Name:</B> Evaki<BR>
<b>Also spelled:</B> Ewaki<BR>
<b>Tribal affiliation:</B> <a href="http://www.native-languages.org/bakairi.htm">Bakairi</a><BR>
<b>Pronunciation:</B> halfway between eh-vah-kee and eh-wah-kee<BR>
<b>Type:</B> <a href="http://www.native-languages.org/goddesses.htm">Goddess</a>, 
<a href="http://www.native-languages.org/legends-night.htm">night</a>, 
<a href="http://www.native-languages.org/legends-dreams.htm">dreams</a>, 
<a href="http://www.native-languages.org/legends-bat.htm">bat god</a><BR> 
<BR>
</font>

Evaki is the Bakairi night goddess, aunt of the twin culture heroes 
<a href="http://www.native-languages.org/keri.htm">Keri</a> and 
<a href="http://www.native-languages.org/kame.htm">Kame</a>. Evaki has the responsibility
of taking the sun out of the jar it is kept in every morning and putting it back away at night. Evaki is 
associated with sleep and dreams, and she is sometimes represented as a bat.

